With this idea of universal empire is combined a reverence for antiquity‚ for old customs, for the religious saith of early Italy, and an attachment to all places connected with the his- tory of the nation.

The Aeneid then, as an epic describing the great part Rome played in the history of· the world, as determined by the divine decrees, is partly a national and partly a religious epic.
